[1] Case update
- Wed 18 Dec 2019. CMRE (Comite Multisectoriel de la Riposte a la maladie a virus Ebola)
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://mailchi.mp/c4f62fb7baff/situation-pidmiologique-du-18-dcembre-2019?e=37a53d5a9e

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 17 Dec 2019:

Since the start of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 3351, of which 3233 are confirmed and 118 probable. In total, there were 2217 deaths (2099 confirmed and 118 probable) and 1091 people healed.
- 452 suspected cases under investigation;
- 2 new confirmed cases in North Kivu, including 1 in Butembo and 1 in Mabalako;
- 3 new deaths including 1 community death in Mabalako and 2 deaths of confirmed cases in the Ebola treatment center (ETC) in North Kivu in Mabalako;
- 2 cured people leaving the ETC in North Kivu in Beni;
- No health worker is among the new confirmed cases. The cumulative number of confirmed/probable cases among health workers is 164 (5% of all confirmed/probable cases), including 41 deaths;
- Butembo again reported a confirmed case after 54 days of silence. The last case was reported on 23 Oct 2019.

News
----
Butembo sub-coordination reports confirmed Ebola case after 54 days:
- She is a 23-year-old woman, alive and unvaccinated, from the Aloya health area in Mabalako in North Kivu. She was listed as the contact for a confirmed case of 13 Dec 2019, whose date of onset of signs dates back to 6 Dec 2019. This contact had never been seen or found to be vaccinated (not vaccinated);
- This woman went to Butembo in the Vutsundo health area to visit her older sister on 15 Dec 2019;
- The start date for signs at her home dates back to 11 Dec 2019 with the exhibition period from 24 Nov to 7 Dec 2019;
- She was consulted on 11 Dec 2019 in a health facility not yet identified in Kantine, in Aloya to continue her treatment with the drugs provided by the home health structure from 12 to 14 Dec 2019;
- This woman moved to Butembo in the Vutsundo health area on 15 Dec 2019, where she was seen as an outpatient from 15 to 16 Dec 2019 at the Wasingya health post in Vutsundo in the Butembo health zone with clinical signs of anorexia, dysphagia, chest pain and myalgia;
- On 17 Dec 2019, there were persistent signs and she went to be consulted at another health post, notably Notre Dame de Grace to Mama Musayi in Butembo, where the alert was launched. She was investigated and validated, but the patient refused to be transferred to the ETC;
- The sample taken in this health facility returned positive for Ebola virus disease on the same day, and the patient was transferred to the ETC of Butembo after reluctance was lifted;
- A total of 19 contacts were pre-listed around this woman, including 10 members of her family, 4 co-patients and 5 healthcare providers;
- As for decontamination, the patient's household and the health structure she visited in Aloya are being identified in Mabalako; her sister's household in Vutsundo in Butembo, Wasingya and Notre Dame de Grace were decontaminated this Wednesday [18 Dec 2019];
- The vaccination around this case is scheduled for Friday [20 Dec 2019] in Mabalako, while in Butembo, a vaccination ring was performed on 17 Dec 2019.

Vaccination
-----------
- A total of 2381 people were vaccinated, as of 16 Dec 2019, with the 2nd vaccine Ad26.ZEBOV/MVA-BN-Filo (Johnson & Johnson) in the 2 health areas from Karisimbi to Goma;
- Since the start of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018 with the rVSV-ZEBOV vaccine, 257 953 people have been vaccinated.

Entry point surveillance
-------------------------
- Since the start of the epidemic, the total number of travelers checked (temperature taken) at health checkpoints has been 129 849 674;
- To date, a total of 109 entry points (PoE) and health control points (PoC) have been established in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri in order to protect the country's major cities and avoid the spread of the epidemic in neighboring countries.

