- Tue 17 Dec 2019. DRC: Ebola virus disease - external situation report 72
[WHO/AFRO Health Emergency Information and Risk Assessment, abridged, edited]
https://tinyurl.com/tk6g438

In the week of 9-15 Dec 2019, 24 new confirmed Ebola virus disease (EVD) cases were reported from 3 health zones in 2 affected provinces in the Democratic Republic of the Congo. The majority of these new confirmed cases are from Mabalako (22 of 24; 92%), and the other cases were reported from Biena (1 of 24; 4%) and Mandima (1 of 24; 4%) health zones.

The new cases from Mabalako and Biena are linked to a single chain of transmission, in which one individual was a potential source of infection for 24 people. This was the 2nd documentation of EVD illness in this individual within a 6-month period. Based on the preliminary sequencing of samples from the case, this is being classified as a relapse of EVD. Rare cases of relapse have been documented, in which a person who has recovered from EVD gets disease symptoms again, but this is the 1st documented relapse in this outbreak.

The volume of alerts reported has returned to levels seen before the security incidents in the past weeks. In general, the overall average proportion of contacts under surveillance in the last 7 days has returned to previously observed levels. However, Mabalako, the health zone with the highest volume of contacts, has the lowest performance with 73% of contacts under surveillance.

In the past 21 days (25 Nov to 15 Dec 2019), 45 confirmed cases were reported from 13 of the 87 health areas within 5 neighboring active health zones in North Kivu and Ituri provinces: Mabalako (67%; n = 30 cases), Mandima (16%; n = 7), Beni (13%; n = 6), Oicha (2%; n = 1), and Biena (2%; n = 1). More than half (53%, n = 24) of the cases over the last 21 days have a known epidemiological link to the same transmission chain from Aloya health area in the Mabalako health zone.

As of 15 Dec 2019, a total of 3348 EVD cases, including 3230 confirmed and 118 probable cases, have been reported, of which 2213 cases died (overall case fatality ratio, 66%). Of the total confirmed and probable cases, 56% (1883) were female, 28% (941) were children aged less than 18 years, and 5% (169) were healthcare workers.

