- Thu 19 Dec 2019. Interview: David Gressly
[Radio Okapi, in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.radiookapi.net/2019/12/19/actualite/politique/david-gressly-si-veut-vraiment-mettre-fin-ebola-biakato-il-faut-avoir

David Gressly: "If we really want to end Ebola in Biakato, we must have access to this area."

The United Nations Coordinator for emergency interventions for Ebola in the DRC, David Gressly, undertook a mission on Wednesday [18 Dec 2019] for a few hours in Aloya in North Kivu. In this interview with Radio Okapi, he speaks about the launch of a joint United Nations plan to fight Ebola in Biakato in Ituri. This area is considered to be the current focus of the epidemic. To end this disease, David Gressly thinks "we must have access to this area".

Radio Okapi (RO): You have just made a few hours visit to Aloya in North Kivu, what did you observe on the ground and what was the purpose of your visit to this locality?

David Gressly (DG): In fact, the objective of my visit was to better understand the current situation on the side of the response to Ebola, and also on the security level. So we had good discussions with the customary chiefs, with the security forces, with the citizens too, and I believe that the situation remains serious, I was impressed by the response by the Congolese on the site.

RO: In recent weeks, we have seen that the Ebola response teams have been the target of attacks by men in Biakato in the province of Ituri, there have even been deaths of men, have you fears that if these attacks continue, may this affect the response to Ebola?

DG: Of course it will have an impact, we can't deny that. But as I said about the situation in Aloya, even in Biakato we saw Congolese who continued the work especially at CTA and now it starts again with vaccinations.

RO: Today, at the United Nations level, is the identity of the attackers who attack the Ebola treatment centers in Lwemba, in Biakato, in Mangina known?

DG: We are working with the Security Forces but also and above all the military prosecutors either in Beni, or in Bunia depending on the qualities to give technical and logistical support for the prosecution of the criminals who were behind these attacks.

RO: David Gressly, the United Nations has just announced the launch of a joint plan to fight Ebola in Biakato in the province of Ituri. What was this plan?

DG: In fact, it is to find a way for the return to Biakato and Lwemba, which were important foci among the last foci of this epidemic. There were problems with having access to substance, especially in Lwemba in the response. So, if we really want to end this epidemic we must have access to this area, to start with, on the government side, we have already sent additional forces, MONUSCO has done the same thing, I believe that together they have secured the city of Biakato and the government used this as a basis to go forward towards Lwemba with negotiations, discussions, commitments with the population which went well yesterday and it will continue, so I believe with this device, this airlift, with the security forces, we are going to have a success in this area.

--
